name: Meadow Lane
description: The route to the ground is signposted 'Football and Cricket Traffic' from all directions.

name: Gateshead International Stadium
description: Gateshead FC have played at the International Stadium since moving from Redheugh Park during the 1971/72 season. An all-seated venue, the International Stadium boasts a capacity of 11,800.

name: York Community Stadium
description: This community stadium leisure complex heralded a new era for sports and  community services in the city. It provided a new football and rugby  stadium for professional and community sport as well as leisure facilities  for York.

name: Recreation Ground
alternateName: The EBB Stadium at the Recreation Ground

sponsor.name: The EBB Stadium at the Recreation Ground

name: Cherrywood Road
description: Over the last few years the Easy As HGV Stadium has undergone - and is undergoing - a major transformation. The tired old stands have either gone or been completely refurbished.

name: Spencer Stadium
alternateName: The Banbury Plant Hire Community Stadium

sponsor.name: The Banbury Plant Hire Community Stadium

description: The restricted access to the ground can lead to long delays in and around the station when leaving after matches, especially on Saturdays. Town centre car parks are up to 15 minutes walk from the ground.

name: New Bucks Head
description: New Bucks Head stadium is considered to be amongst the best non-league  grounds in the country and holds a football league 'A' grading.

name: Plainmoor
description: Plainmoor Stadium is situated in St Marychurch, an area of Torquay that is within walking distance of Torquay town centre.

name: Victoria Road
description: Victoria Road has existed as a football ground since 1917, when the  Sterling Works side, whose factory was situated alongside, used it.

name: Haig Avenue
description: The nearest railway station is Meols Cop on the Manchester to Southport line which is a ten minute walk from the ground.

name: Mill Farm
description: Mill Farm also has 3G pitches for both football and hockey.  Mill Farm is also home to Fylde Hockey Club.

name: Deva Stadium
description: Located outside the city centre in the Sealand Road Industrial Estate, the  stadium is notable for straddling the England-Wales border. The pitch  itself is in Wales (Flintshire), with the front gates and main office  in England.

name: Clarence Park
description: Clarence Park has always enjoyed a reputation for having one of the finest playing surfaces in non-league football, even the early match reports praise the high quality of St Albans home pitch to the detriment of other grounds. Down the years a large number of clubs heading for Wembley to play in the FA Cup final have stopped off at Clarence Park the day before the final for a spot of training.

name: War Memorial Sports Ground
description: Carshalton British Rail Station is five minutes walk from the ground.

name: Jakemans Community Stadium
description: Matchday car parking at the Jakemans Community Stadium is exclusively for  car park season pass holders and club guests in season 2022-2023. Further  car parking spaces will become available following the completion of  construction works at the Community Stadium in the future.

name: Broadhurst Park
description: Broadhurst Park is the UK's first new ground to be built and funded by a supporter-owned football club.

name: Woodside Park
alternateName: R & D Advisors UK Ltd Stadium

sponsor.name: R & D Advisors UK Ltd Stadium

description: The grandstand is covered and all seated with the addition of press facilities and directors box.

name: Nyewood Lane
description: The ground is situated in Nyewood Lane, Bognor Regis - a short distance from both the seafront and the town centre and railway station.

name: Victory Park
alternateName: The Chorley Group Victory Park Stadium

sponsor.name: The Chorley Group Victory Park Stadium

description: Victory Park is named after the outcome of World War One, with work  beginning on the ground (an old ash tip) in 1919 and the Club moving in a  year later after buying the land for £868.

name: Ewen Fields
description: In 2014, Benfica visited Ewen Fields for a UEFA Youth League Quarter Final  fixture against Manchester City.

name: Cressing Road
description: The ground has a recently extended Main Seated Stand that can accommodate 553 spectators including six wheelchair spaces. The Clubhouse End of the ground has recently been upgraded with a new terrace. This end of the ground can accommodate 1,131 spectators.

name: Gallagher Stadium
description: The Gallagher Stadium is minutes away from the town centre, where you'll find more shops than there is at Bluewater. The ground is seconds away from the River Medway and the beautiful Whatman Park.

name: Tameside Stadium
description: The ground has two covered stands and is fully terraced on all four sides  and currently holds the FA 'B' Grading.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Grosvenor Vale
description: It's recommended that supporters travel to Grosvenor Vale via public transport as the club is remarkably well served by tube, train and bus routes.

name: Stainton Park
description: The stadium has been home to Radcliffe Football Club since 1970 and the ground has played host to many famous teams and footballers over the years.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Nethermoor Park
description: Nethermoor is about five minutes' flat walk from Guiseley station.  It is very well served on the Wharfedale Line by trains from Leeds, Bradford and Ilkley.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: York Road
description: Maidenhead United FC play at York Road, a ground which has been their home  since 1871. The ground is situated in the centre of Maidenhead, close to  the town centre and the railway station. Unfortunately, there is no parking  available at York Road Stadium.

name: North Street
description: Pay and display parking is available on Rogers Lane and also at Severn  Square, both are a 5-10 minute walk from the arena.

name: Giant Axe
description: Giant Axe stadium has been the club's home since the early days, but has been heavily renovated since the mid to late 1990s. The 513-seat Main Stand, which used be a standing terrace, was converted into a modern all-seater stand and was renamed The John Bagguley Stand in 2011 after the club's late Life President.

name: Weaver Stadium
description: Visitors can take in the sights of Nantwich Town Centre on the way to the ground, which is an historic market town with the impressive St Mary's Church and Tudor buildings. There are plenty of places to have lunch and drinks.

description: The club first came to this their present site in 2013 which is being shared with United Counties League Division One outfit, Burton Park Wanderers FC.

name: Causeway Lane
description: The Proctor Cars Stadium is just 500 yards from the town centre. With that in mind, parking at the Ground is limited to special match days only. For evening matches parking is available on Causeway Lane right outside the ground on a first come first serve basis.

description: Opened in 2019, the stadium features two top quality 3G playing surfaces built using the latest artificial pitch technology, a covered 300-seater stand, covered standing areas behind each goal and two further covered stands down one side, including seating for 50 spectators.
